    short_definition: 'Glen Plaid, also known as Glen Urquhart check, is a traditional Scottish woven pattern combining small and large checks in a distinctive, layered arrangement. It is one of the most enduring patterns in British suiting.',
    full_definition: `Glen Plaid — formally known as Glen Urquhart check — is one of the most storied patterns in the history of British tailoring. Its origins lie in the Scottish Highlands, where it was first woven in the early nineteenth century on the Urquhart estate in Glenurquhart, Inverness-shire. The pattern rose to international prominence when it was adopted by the Prince of Wales (later King Edward VIII) in the 1920s and 1930s, cementing its place as a hallmark of aristocratic British style.

The pattern itself is a complex, multi-scale check formed by alternating bands of small houndstooth-style weave with larger plain or twill blocks. The result is a richly layered visual effect that changes character depending on viewing distance — up close, the intricate sub-pattern is clearly visible; from a distance, the cloth reads as a soft, tonal check. Traditional Glen Plaid is woven in wool, typically in earthy tones of grey, brown, and cream, often with a thin overcheck in a contrasting colour such as red or blue.

In suiting, Glen Plaid occupies a versatile position between the formality of a plain cloth and the relaxed character of a bolder pattern. A grey or charcoal Glen Plaid suit is appropriate for business meetings, country weekends, and smart-casual occasions alike. The pattern's visual complexity rewards close inspection while remaining entirely appropriate in professional settings.

Glen Plaid wears beautifully in medium-weight wool. The pattern tends to flatter a range of body types by breaking up the silhouette without introducing the distracting busyness of heavier checks. When lined properly and cut with attention to pattern matching at the seams, a Glen Plaid suit represents some of the finest work a British tailor can produce.`,
