    full_definition: `Chalk stripe is one of the great patterns of British tailoring, synonymous with the distinguished suiting traditions of the City of London and Savile Row. The pattern takes its name from the appearance of its stripes, which are wide and slightly diffuse — as though drawn with a stick of chalk rather than a sharp pen — in contrast to the finer, crisper lines of the pinstripe.

The chalk stripe effect is achieved during the weaving process, where threads of a lighter colour — typically cream, white, or pale grey — are woven through a dark worsted background in a regular repeat. The spacing between stripes is generally wider than in a traditional pinstripe, and the stripe itself is composed of a cluster of threads rather than a single needle-sharp line, giving it that characteristic soft, chalky quality. Dark navy and charcoal chalk stripe suits have long been the uniform of British professionals and politicians.

Historically, chalk stripe became particularly fashionable in the 1930s and 1940s, when broad-shouldered, single-breasted suits in flannel and worsted were the standard of business dress. The pattern fell from favour for a period but has enjoyed numerous revivals, most recently as part of a broader renewed appreciation for classic British tailoring. Today, a chalk stripe suit carries connotations of authority, confidence, and sartorial knowledge.

The cloth wears with considerable gravitas. The vertical lines of the stripe create an elongating optical illusion that flatters most silhouettes, and the bold pattern allows for confident, considered styling. A navy chalk stripe suit pairs beautifully with a white shirt and solid tie for the full City effect, or can be dressed down with an open collar for a modern, relaxed interpretation. Double-breasted cuts suit chalk stripe particularly well, as the wide lapels complement the broad spacing of the stripe.`,
