    full_definition: `Super 150s wool sits at the summit of woven suiting fabrics, representing a level of fibre fineness that was virtually unattainable for most of textile history and remains the exclusive territory of the world's finest mills. The "Super" grading system for wool was developed in the twentieth century to classify fibres according to the diameter of their individual strands, measured in microns. Super 150s wool contains fibres of approximately 15.5 microns in diameter — far finer than standard suiting wools, which typically range between 20 and 25 microns.

To contextualise this fineness: a single micron is one thousandth of a millimetre. Human hair averages approximately 70 microns in diameter. The individual fibres in Super 150s wool are therefore extraordinarily fine, softer than cashmere to the touch, and capable of being spun into yarns of remarkable lightness and drape. The finest grades of Super 150s and above come primarily from specially bred Merino sheep in Australia, South Africa, and New Zealand, where generations of selective breeding have produced animals with exceptionally fine fleece.

Cloth woven from Super 150s wool possesses qualities that are immediately evident to the touch and eye. It is extraordinarily lightweight — a well-constructed Super 150s suit can weigh less than 700 grams in total — and the drape is fluid and natural in a way that heavier wools cannot replicate. The surface has a lustrous quality that reflects light beautifully, and the handle is incomparably soft against the skin, making it the preferred choice for travel suits and garments worn in warmer conditions or over long periods.

The trade-off for this extraordinary fineness is that Super 150s wool requires careful handling and skilled construction. The very fineness that makes it so appealing also makes it more susceptible to wear, abrasion, and distortion under heavy use. A Super 150s suit is best reserved for occasions where its qualities can be appreciated — board meetings, formal dinners, international travel — rather than for everyday use that would accelerate wear of the delicate fibres.`,
    properties: 'Fibre grade: Super 150s (approx. 15.5 microns)\nFibre origin: Merino sheep (Australia, NZ, South Africa)\nWeight: 160–220 gsm\nHandle: Exceptionally soft, silky\nFormality: Business formal to formal',
