    full_definition: `Alpaca is one of the most prized natural fibres in the world of luxury menswear, combining softness, warmth, and lustre in a way that few other fibres can match. The fibre is harvested from the alpaca, a domesticated camelid that has been raised in the high Andean plateaux of Peru, Bolivia, and Ecuador for thousands of years. The Inca civilisation considered alpaca fibre — particularly that of the rare Suri alpaca — to be the fibre of the gods, reserving its finest forms for royalty and religious ceremony.

There are two breeds of alpaca used in fibre production. The Huacaya, the more common breed, produces a fluffy, crimped fibre that processes into soft, springy yarns ideal for knitwear. The rarer Suri produces long, silky, straight fibres with a remarkable natural lustre, used in woven fabrics where fineness and sheen are prized. The finest alpaca fibres — Baby Alpaca, which refers not to the age of the animal but to the first shearing of its finest fleece — measure between 18 and 22 microns in diameter, placing them in the same rarefied company as cashmere.

Alpaca fibre has several remarkable natural properties. It is significantly warmer than sheep's wool for its weight, owing to the hollow structure of each fibre, which traps air and provides exceptional thermal insulation. It is also naturally lanolin-free, making it hypoallergenic and comfortable for those who react to conventional wool. The fibre's natural colours — which range from white through brown, grey, and black — are exceptionally rich, and alpaca takes dye beautifully, producing colours of unusual depth and vibrancy.

In menswear, alpaca appears most frequently in knitwear — jumpers, cardigans, and scarves — where its softness and drape can be fully appreciated. It also features in woven suiting cloths, particularly in blends with wool or silk, where it contributes lightness and a subtle sheen. An alpaca overcoat or travel jacket combines practicality with luxury in a way that few other fabrics achieve.`,
