    seo_description: 'Silk is the world\'s finest natural fibre, spun by silkworms and woven into lustrous, luxurious cloth. Discover its properties, history, and role in menswear.',
    short_definition: 'Silk is a natural protein fibre produced by the silkworm during the formation of its cocoon. It is the finest and most lustrous of all natural fibres, valued in menswear for its incomparable sheen, softness, and drape.',
    full_definition: `Silk is the oldest and most universally celebrated luxury textile in human history, with a continuous tradition of production that stretches back over five thousand years to ancient China. The fibre is produced by the silkworm — the larva of the domesticated moth Bombyx mori — which spins a continuous thread of protein filament up to one kilometre in length to form its cocoon. It is this single, unbroken filament, reeled from the cocoon and twisted with others to form yarn, that gives silk its extraordinary fineness, strength, and lustre.

The optical properties of silk are unique among natural fibres. Each filament has a triangular cross-section that functions as a prism, refracting and reflecting light in a way that produces the characteristic shimmering, almost iridescent sheen for which silk has been prized throughout history. This effect is impossible to replicate fully in synthetic fibres, which is why silk remains the benchmark against which all lustrous textiles are measured.

Silk is used across a remarkable range of menswear applications. In shirting, silk produces garments of extraordinary softness and temperature-regulating ability — cool to the touch in warm conditions and surprisingly insulating in cold. Silk neckwear has been the standard of quality for ties, pocket squares, and cravats for over a century, prized for its ability to hold a knot cleanly and its richness of colour and pattern. In linings, silk provides the smoothness and lightness that allows a tailored jacket to slip easily over a shirt and drape naturally from the shoulder.

Silk blends with wool, cotton, and cashmere to produce suiting cloths of exceptional quality, contributing lustre, drape, and a cool, smooth hand to the finished fabric. A silk-wool blend suit is one of the finest choices available for formal occasions and warmer-weather dressing, combining the structure of wool with the lightness and sheen of silk.`,
