    seo_title: 'What is Cotton Poplin? | William Ashford',
    seo_description: 'Cotton poplin is a smooth, tightly woven shirting fabric with a fine ribbed texture. Learn why it is the most popular shirting cloth in British menswear.',
    short_definition: 'Cotton poplin is a smooth, closely woven shirting fabric made using a plain weave with a higher warp thread count than weft, producing a characteristic fine crosswise rib and a crisp, lustrous surface. It is the most widely used shirting cloth in quality menswear.',
    full_definition: `Cotton poplin is the workhorse fabric of the quality dress shirt, combining the crispness, smoothness, and clean appearance that formal and business shirts demand with a durability and ease of care that suits the realities of regular wear. It is the cloth against which all other shirting fabrics are measured, and for many wearers it remains the unchallenged choice for business shirts, formal shirts, and any occasion where a sharp, clean appearance is required.

The name "poplin" has disputed origins — some sources trace it to Poperinge in Belgium, a historic centre of textile production, whilst others link it to the papal town of Avignon, where a similar cloth was produced in the Middle Ages. Whatever the etymology, the fabric's construction is well defined: poplin is a plain-weave cloth in which the warp threads are significantly finer and more numerous than the weft threads. This differential creates a fine, horizontal rib across the surface of the cloth — visible under close inspection — whilst the overall surface reads as smooth, flat, and slightly lustrous.

In shirting, cotton poplin is typically woven from two-ply cotton yarns, where two fine threads are twisted together before weaving. Two-ply yarns produce a more even, stronger fabric than single-ply equivalents and are the standard of quality British shirtmaking. The finest poplin shirts use long-staple Egyptian or Sea Island cotton, which produces fibres of extraordinary length and fineness, resulting in a cloth of silky smoothness and exceptional lustre.

Poplin shirts press beautifully to a crisp, sharp finish that holds throughout a working day. The fabric is robust enough to withstand frequent laundering at appropriate temperatures and retains its appearance well over time when properly cared for. Its smooth surface makes it ideal for formal wear under a suit or dinner jacket, where a clean, flat shirt front is essential. A white cotton poplin dress shirt is, simply, one of the most correct and versatile garments in menswear.`,
