    short_definition: 'Piqué is a fabric characterised by a raised, textured surface pattern — typically a waffle, honeycomb, or fine cord — created by a specific weaving or knitting technique. In menswear, it is most famously used for formal dress shirt fronts and polo shirts.',
    full_definition: `Piqué is a fabric of considerable versatility and distinction, appearing in contexts as different as the white tie dress shirt and the weekend polo shirt, and performing admirably in both. The name derives from the French piquer, meaning to prick or quilt, and refers to the raised, textured surface that is the fabric's defining characteristic. This texture is not applied or printed but arises directly from the structure of the weave or knit, giving genuine piqué its characteristic three-dimensional quality.

In its woven form, piqué is produced using a compound weave that creates a raised pattern of cords, wales, or cellular honeycomb structures. The most formal variety — marcella piqué — is a white cotton fabric with a fine waffle or birdseye-like cell structure, used almost exclusively for the fronts and cuffs of formal dress shirts worn with black tie and white tie. The texture of marcella piqué serves a practical purpose as well as an aesthetic one: the raised surface helps the shirt front retain its crisp, upright appearance over the course of an evening, resisting the tendency of plain cotton to go limp under the warmth of a waistcoat and jacket.

Knitted piqué — most familiar as the fabric of the polo shirt — uses a looser, more elastic construction that produces a similar visual texture with considerably more stretch and comfort. This version of piqué has been a staple of British smart-casual dressing since the sport shirt was adapted into everyday wear in the early twentieth century.

The weave or knit structure of piqué gives it excellent breathability, as the raised surface creates air pockets that allow heat and moisture to dissipate. In formal wear, this makes it a more practical choice for evening than flat cotton, whilst in casual knitwear it contributes to the shirt's comfort in warm conditions. A well-made marcella piqué dress shirt front, properly starched and pressed, is one of the most visually striking elements of correct black-tie or white-tie dress — crisp, textured, and unmistakably formal.`,
